stylometry: Normal Distribution - This fits a data set to the normal curve including a mean and standard deviation. The shape of this distribution is a normal bell curve where each side is equal to the other (0.5 and 0.5) and the entire set adds up to 1.0 or 100%. One of the most important things to look at in the normal curve is the standard deviation, as it shows how much the data set is represented by the model. If the standard deviation is too large, then the data may be too varied to be correct. Also the normal distribution relies on the "z" value for many of its equations. This can be used to find the area of part the bell curve.
